column_contents: From Clingmans Dome Parking Area follow paved trail towards the lookout tower.  Past the visitor center about 0.2 mile  there is a concrete bench on the right side of the trail.  This bench is the first reference point to a Red Spruce with a diameter of 21.2 cm.  It is about 50 meters at 20 degrees from the bench..  The next tree is a Red Spruce with a diameter of 50.2 cm at 25 degrees.  This Spruce is on the ridge.  The next Spruce is about 30 meters at 38 degrees with a diameter of 23 cm. From this tree the top right corner of the hectare ATBI Plot is 55 degrees at about 25 meters.  This corner is marked with a thin red electric fence post about 3 feet tall.  All tree tags are marked "ATBI".  The hectare is marked off with nylon string around the parameter.  The Long Term Monitoring Plot is also marked with string.  Do not disturb the Long Term Monitoring Plot.

column_contents: From Clingmans Dome Parking Area follow paved trail towards the lookout tower.  Past the visitor center about 0.2 mile  there is a concrete bench on the right side of the trail.  This bench is the first reference point to a Red Spruce with a diameter of 21.2 cm.  It is about 50 meters at 20 degrees from the bench..  The next tree is a Red Spruce with a diameter of 50.2 cm at 25 degrees.  This Spruce is on the ridge.  The next Spruce is about 30 meters at 38 degrees with a diameter of 23 cm. From this tree the top right corner of the hectare ATBI Plot is 55 degrees at about 25 meters.  This corner is marked with a thin red electric fence post about 3 feet tall.  All tree tags are marked "ATBI".  The hectare is marked off with nylon string around the parameter.  The Long Term Monitoring Plot is also marked with string.  Do not disturb the Long Term Monitoring Plot.

This bench is the first reference point to a Red Spruce with a diameter of 21.2 cm.  It is about 50 meters at 20 degrees from the bench..  The next tree is a Red Spruce with a diameter of 50.2 cm at 25 degrees.  This Spruce is on the ridge.  The next Spruce is about 30 meters at 38 degrees with a diameter of 23 cm. Do not disturb the Long Term Monitoring Plot.

column_contents: along trail to Clingmans Dome lookout tower
UTM coordinates were converted from NAD27 to NAD83

From Clingmans Dome Parking Area follow paved trail towards the lookout tower.  Past the visitor center about 0.2 mile  there is a concrete bench on the right side of the trail.  This bench is the first reference point to a Red Spruce with a diameter of 21.2 cm.  It is about 50 meters at 20 degrees from the bench..  The next tree is a Red Spruce with a diameter of 50.2 cm at 25 degrees.  This Spruce is on the ridge.  The next Spruce is about 30 meters at 38 degrees with a diameter of 23 cm. From this tree the top right corner of the hectare ATBI Plot is 55 degrees at about 25 meters.  This corner is marked with a thin red electric fence post about 3 feet tall.  All tree tags are marked "ATBI".  The hectare is marked off with nylon string around the parameter.  The Long Term Monitoring Plot is also marked with string.  Do not disturb the Long Term Monitoring Plot.

From Clingmans Dome Parking Area follow paved trail towards the lookout tower.  Past the visitor center about 0.2 mile  there is a concrete bench on the right side of the trail.  This bench is the first reference point to a Red Spruce with a diameter of 21.2 cm.  It is about 50 meters at 20 degrees from the bench..  The next tree is a Red Spruce with a diameter of 50.2 cm at 25 degrees.  This Spruce is on the ridge.  The next Spruce is about 30 meters at 38 degrees with a diameter of 23 cm. From this tree the top right corner of the hectare ATBI Plot is 55 degrees at about 25 meters.  This corner is marked with a thin red electric fence post about 3 feet tall.  All tree tags are marked "ATBI".  The hectare is marked off with nylon string around the parameter.  The Long Term Monitoring Plot is also marked with string.  Do not disturb the Long Term Monitoring Plot.

column_contents: From Clingmans Dome Parking Area follow paved trail towards the lookout tower.  Past the visitor center about 0.2 mile  there is a concrete bench on the right side of the trail.  This bench is the first reference point to a Red Spruce with a diameter of 21.2 cm.  It is about 50 meters at 20 degrees from the bench..  The next tree is a Red Spruce with a diameter of 50.2 cm at 25 degrees.  This Spruce is on the ridge.  The next Spruce is about 30 meters at 38 degrees with a diameter of 23 cm. From this tree the top right corner of the hectare ATBI Plot is 55 degrees at about 25 meters.  This corner is marked with a thin red electric fence post about 3 feet tall.  All tree tags are marked "ATBI".  The hectare is marked off with nylon string around the parameter.  The Long Term Monitoring Plot is also marked with string.  Do not disturb the Long Term Monitoring Plot.

along trail to Clingmans Dome lookout tower

From Clingmans Dome Parking Area follow paved trail towards the lookout tower.  Past the visitor center about 0.2 mile  there is a concrete bench on the right side of the trail.  This bench is the first reference point to a Red Spruce with a diameter of 21.2 cm.  It is about 50 meters at 20 degrees from the bench..  The next tree is a Red Spruce with a diameter of 50.2 cm at 25 degrees.  This Spruce is on the ridge.  The next Spruce is about 30 meters at 38 degrees with a diameter of 23 cm. From this tree the top right corner of the hectare ATBI Plot is 55 degrees at about 25 meters.  This corner is marked with a thin red electric fence post about 3 feet tall.  All tree tags are marked "ATBI".  The hectare is marked off with nylon string around the parameter.  The Long Term Monitoring Plot is also marked with string.  Do not disturb the Long Term Monitoring Plot.

column_contents: along trail to Clingmans Dome lookout tower

From Clingmans Dome Parking Area follow paved trail towards the lookout tower.  Past the visitor center about 0.2 mile  there is a concrete bench on the right side of the trail.  This bench is the first reference point to a Red Spruce with a diameter of 21.2 cm.  It is about 50 meters at 20 degrees from the bench..  The next tree is a Red Spruce with a diameter of 50.2 cm at 25 degrees.  This Spruce is on the ridge.  The next Spruce is about 30 meters at 38 degrees with a diameter of 23 cm. From this tree the top right corner of the hectare ATBI Plot is 55 degrees at about 25 meters.  This corner is marked with a thin red electric fence post about 3 feet tall.  All tree tags are marked "ATBI".  The hectare is marked off with nylon string around the parameter.  The Long Term Monitoring Plot is also marked with string.  Do not disturb the Long Term Monitoring Plot.

From Clingmans Dome Parking Area follow paved trail towards the lookout tower.  Past the visitor center about 0.2 mile  there is a concrete bench on the right side of the trail.  This bench is the first reference point to a Red Spruce with a diameter of 21.2 cm.  It is about 50 meters at 20 degrees from the bench..  The next tree is a Red Spruce with a diameter of 50.2 cm at 25 degrees.  This Spruce is on the ridge.  The next Spruce is about 30 meters at 38 degrees with a diameter of 23 cm. From this tree the top right corner of the hectare ATBI Plot is 55 degrees at about 25 meters.  This corner is marked with a thin red electric fence post about 3 feet tall.  All tree tags are marked "ATBI".  The hectare is marked off with nylon string around the parameter.  The Long Term Monitoring Plot is also marked with string.  Do not disturb the Long Term Monitoring Plot.

question: For each vehicle, show the road speed limit, the highest speed the vehicle was recorded by the event data recorder, and how much higher or lower than the speed limit the vehicle was traveling. Limit travel speed and speedlimit to values less than 300 kph.
text: For each vehicle, show the road speed limit, the highest speed the vehicle was recorded by the event data recorder, and how much higher or lower than the speed limit the vehicle was traveling. Limit travel speed and speedlimit to values less than 300 kph.
sql: SELECT SPEEDLIMIT, MAXSPEED, MAXSPEED - SPEEDLIMIT DIFF FROM GV JOIN ( 	SELECT CASEID, VEHNO, MAX(PVALUE) MAXSPEED FROM EDRPRECRASH 	WHERE PCODE = 1010 AND PVALUE < 300 	GROUP BY CASEID, VEHNO ) S ON GV.CASEID = S.CASEID AND GV.VEHNO = S.VEHNO WHERE SPEEDLIMIT < 300

question: Show the total occupant count and the mortality count by belt use category. A mortality occured (was fatal) indicated by lookup code 1.
text: Show the total occupant count and the mortality count by belt use category. A mortality occured (was fatal) indicated by lookup code 1.

question: List the number of crashes by vehicle make from most to least. Show how many of these crashes resulted in a fire. Calculate the proportion of total crashes by make to crashes with a fire
text: List the number of crashes by vehicle make from most to least. Show how many of these crashes resulted in a fire. Calculate the proportion of total crashes by make to crashes with a fire
sql: SELECT MAKE, COUNT(*) AS CASE_COUNT, SUM(FIRE) AS FIRE_COUNT, (CAST(SUM(FIRE) AS FLOAT)/ CAST(COUNT(*) AS FLOAT)) AS FIRE_PROPORTION FROM VPICDECODE VD 	JOIN FIRE F ON F.CASEID = VD.CASEID AND F.VEHNO = VD.VEHNO GROUP BY MAKE ORDER BY FIRE_PROPORTION DESC

text: What is the 2022 federal expenditure per student at the public high school with the highest english language learner count in the All Students sub group in their english language program? Include the school name, language learner count, and federal expenditure per student in the result.

column_contents: 411 2017 HALE detection records were updated to Chlorodrepanis virens wilsoni.
Imported the 2017 non-HALE Maui Forest Bird Recovery Project stations and data into the database.

The wrong subspecies of Amakihi was entered for 2017 HALE Amakihi detections.Chlorodrepanis virens virens was entered for 2017 HALE bird detections when the correct subspecies is Chlorodrepanis virens wilsoni.
Moving forward bird surveys on Maui will be in cooperation with partners, so need to have all the bird data together in the database.  Non-NPS data will not be released to the public.
Changed back to Eurasian Skylark, which is what is in IOC v10.2.  Not sure why it was changed to begin with.
Updated species code to match updated common name.

411 2017 HALE detection records were updated to Chlorodrepanis virens wilsoni.
Imported the 2017 non-HALE Maui Forest Bird Recovery Project stations and data into the database.

The wrong subspecies of Amakihi was entered for 2017 HALE Amakihi detections.Chlorodrepanis virens virens was entered for 2017 HALE bird detections when the correct subspecies is Chlorodrepanis virens wilsoni.
Moving forward bird surveys on Maui will be in cooperation with partners, so need to have all the bird data together in the database.  Non-NPS data will not be released to the public.

question: What percent of stations has the bird with the common name Hawaii Amakihi been observed at?

question: What is the average canopy height of each species' habitats? Include the common name and scientfic name of each species. Ensure the average has decimal precision.
text: What is the average canopy height of each species' habitats? Include the common name and scientfic name of each species. Ensure the average has decimal precision.
sql: select Scientific_Name, Common_Name, avg(cast(canopy_height as float)) as avg_canopy_height from tbl_habitat hab join tbl_events ev on hab.Event_ID = ev.Event_ID join tbl_Observations obs on obs.Event_ID = ev.Event_ID join tlu_species spec on spec.species_id = obs.species_id group by Scientific_Name, common_name order by Scientific_Name

question: Create a list of species sightings at each station. Include the island, site name, location name, transect and transect type, station, the station's latitude, the event id of the observations, the last names of those who observed as well as their notes, the family, scientific name, common name, and alternate name of each bird observed.
text: Create a list of species sightings at each station. Include the island, site name, location name, transect and transect type, station, the station's latitude, the event id of the observations, the last names of those who observed as well as their notes, the family, scientific name, common name, and alternate name of each bird observed.
sql: select island, site_name, Loc_Name, transect, transect_type, Station, lat_final, te.event_id, last_name, event_notes, family, Scientific_Name, Common_Name, Alternate_Name from tbl_locations tl join tbl_sites ts on tl.Site_ID = ts.Site_ID join tbl_transect tr on tr.Location_ID = tl.Location_ID join tbl_stations st on st.Transect_ID = tr.Transect_ID join tbl_events te on te.station_id = st.station_id join xref_Event_Contacts ec on ec.Event_ID = te.Event_ID join tlu_Contacts con on ec.Contact_ID = con.Contact_ID join tbl_Observations obs on te.Event_ID = obs.Event_ID join tlu_species spc on obs.Species_ID = spc.Species_ID join xref_Species_Alternate_Names spc_alt on spc.Species_ID = spc_alt.Species_ID

question: Which island has the most sightings of the bird with the common name Pacific Kingfisher?
text: Which island has the most sightings of the bird with the common name Pacific Kingfisher?
sql: select top 1 island, count(*) as kingfisher_count from tbl_locations tl join tbl_transect tr on tr.Location_ID = tl.Location_ID join tbl_stations st on st.Transect_ID = tr.Transect_ID join tbl_events te on te.station_id = st.station_id join xref_Event_Contacts ec on ec.Event_ID = te.Event_ID join tlu_Contacts con on ec.Contact_ID = con.Contact_ID join tbl_Observations obs on te.Event_ID = obs.Event_ID join tlu_species spc on obs.Species_ID = spc.Species_ID where common_name = 'Pacific Kingfisher' group by island order by kingfisher_count

column_contents: The Service Call Status dashboard provides different views of service calls being handled by service employees: new service calls for the current date, the trend of service calls, and any calls due today or overdue calls. The Customer Receivables Aging dashboard provides an analysis of a company's accounts receivables and key accounts status. It shows the percentage distribution of overdue receivables and future remit, an historical trend of aging amounts, forecasted remit amounts, and the breakdown of these amounts for the top five customers or sales employees.
